==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|absinthium|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|ἀψίνθιον|lang=grc}}, {{term| ἀσπίνθιον|lang=grc}}. The Ancient Greek word is of uncertain origin, albeit recognized as foreign (E.R. Wharton): underlain by a pre-Greek [[w:Pelasgians#Pelasgian_as_pre-Indo-European|Pelasgian]] word, marked by the non-Indoeuropean consonant complex νθ.
May be from {{etyl|fa|en}} {{term|sc=fa-Arab|اسپند|tr=ispand||wild rue|lang=fa}}. See also [[w:Absinthe#Etymology|Absinthe on Wikipedia]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈsɪn.θi.m̩/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|absinthium}}

# {{context|now|rare|lang=en}} The common [[wormwood]] (''[[Artemisia absinthium]]''), an [[intensely]] bitter herb used in the production of [[absinthe]] and [[vermouth]], and as a [[tonic]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED>{{reference-book|editor=Brown, Lesley | title=The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary | origyear= 1933| edition = 5th | year=2003| publisher=Oxford University Press | location=Oxford, UK | isbn =978-0-19-860575-7 | pages =9 }}</ref>
# The dried leaves and flowering tops of the [[wormwood]] plant; [[absinthe oil]].<ref>{{R:MW3 1976|page=5}}</ref>
